# Code Discipline

## Minimal Footprint
- Fix the bug; don't refactor adjacent code
- Add the feature; don't redesign surrounding architecture
- Three similar lines > premature abstraction
- No half-finished implementations
- No error handling, fallbacks, or validation for scenarios that cannot happen
- Don't design for hypothetical future requirements

## Safe Changes
- Always Read a file before editing it
- For destructive operations (delete, overwrite, force-push, reset): pause and confirm with user first
- If you find unexpected state (unfamiliar files, odd branches), investigate before deleting
- Never skip hooks or safety checks to make obstacles disappear — fix the root cause

## Comments
- Default: write no comments
- Write one short line only when the WHY is non-obvious: a hidden constraint, subtle invariant, or specific bug workaround
- Never write "what the code does" — well-named identifiers already do that

## Dead Code
- Delete unused code completely; don't leave `_old` suffixes, commented-out blocks, or `// removed` markers
- No re-exports for removed types, no compatibility shims — just change the code

## Tests
- Validate at system boundaries (user input, external APIs) — not internal code
- Trust framework guarantees; don't add defensive checks for what the framework already ensures
- Integration tests > mocks where the divergence risk is real (DB migrations, auth flows, network protocols)
